│ The previous fix was too aggressive, disabling valid optimizations for `fshl` and causing  │
│ regression test failures. The core issue is a faulty simplification in                     │
│ `SimplifyDemandedUseBits` for rotate-like `fshl` operations (`fshl(X, X, C)`), which       │
│ incorrectly simplifies the operand `X` based on demanded bits.                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The correct fix is to revert the previous change and instead modify the logic that was     │
│ causing the issue. The problem lies in the `else` block for `fshl` where both operands are │
│ the same. The simplification logic there is flawed. I will replace the body of that `else` │
│ block with a call to the logic for non-equal operands (`if (I->getOperand(0) !=            │
│ I->getOperand(1))`). This is safe because `SimplifyDemandedBits` correctly handles the     │
│ case where the same operand is passed multiple times, and it will correctly compute the    │
│ demanded bits for the single underlying value. This approach is more precise, fixing the   │
│ bug without disabling other valid `fshl` optimizations.                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ I will now apply this more targeted fix.                                                   │
